{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"72ef29e7-5ebf-4807-97ed-c3ad08055dde","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle event mapping** on `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android =>\n    {\n        android.OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnPause\n        });\n        android.OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnStop\n        });\n    });\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios =>\n    {\n        ios.DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs on iOS DidEnterBackground\n        });\n    });\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add the `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` namespace.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- Each handler receives the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call platform APIs directly.\n- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`, `OnCreate`, etc.).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dfdf5557-e31a-429f-b809-5bcded50a4f6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"1438:2950B:699F14B:71F51A4:6A03CC84"},"id":"fe5dc00b-fa42-4dc3-ab93-4ada526083a3","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:57:48.075Z","parentId":"fcd30378-548f-4a37-89d2-e27037677c7d"}
